# **The Social Construction of Programming Languages**

## FIRST DRAFT

# **Abstract**

Programming languages are technological artefacts created to enable the human programmer to more easily instruct a computer.  Since the end of the second world war, a number of languages have been developed, tested, adopted and often abandoned.  This dynamism of the field seems to continue unabated, with many new languages appearing in the TIOBE index.  However, a few languages seem to be relatively stable [(Anon n.d.-c)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?o9NBvU) in the top rankings of this index.    
Given the continuing dynamism of the marketplace for programming languages and the variety available, how have programming languages changed over time and are there social factors contributing to its development over time?  The frameworks from Pinch and Bijker, and Bruno Latour are employed to examine this question.

# 

# **Roadmap**

	In this paper, we will first examine three programming languages as case studies, under the framework developed by Pinch and Bijker.  We will consider whether social forces have contributed to their development over time.  We also consider whether the framework developed by Bruno Latour can contribute to our understanding of this development.

# **Method** 

## **Case Studies**

We can approach the project with case studies revolving around a few major languages and their “challengers”.

1. Java, a language developed by Sun Microsystems and currently owned by Oracle.  It’s main challengers are C\#, Kotlin and Scala.  
2. Javascript, a language developed by Netscape as a utility language to provide programmability for their browser product.  It has been challenged multiple times, by Jscript, Actionscript, Coffeescript, and now by Typescript.  
3. Additionally, we explore the evolution of programming languages in the post-war period.  This involves languages which are no longer in wide use, but are relevant predecessors of many other languages to the current day:  
   1. Algol, a language that was “designed by committee”, and challenged primarily by Fortran, which had been developed by IBM.  Additionally, Algol’s design choices influenced many (most?) languages in common use today.  
   2. Lisp, invented in the late 1950s by John McCarthy at MIT, which was originally intended to be applied to artificial intelligence.  
   3. Simula, invented in the late 1960s, had a great influence on many Object-Oriented Programming languages in use today.

## **Empirical Analysis**

In addition to these case studies, we also rely on empirical analysis done by previous researchers [(Meyerovich and Rabkin 2012\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Naeqbr)).  Another source of data are the yearly TIOBE indices [(Anon n.d.-c)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?CQEODN), which have been collected since 2001\.

## **Prior Work**

The most extensive recent related research found by the author is a series of three papers by [(Meyerovich and Rabkin 2012\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?dY2iIY) that entailed both qualitative and quantitative research.  Curiously enough, although Socio-PLT [(Meyerovich and Rabkin 2012\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?qkLXCN) argues in favour of leveraging decades of social science research in order to understand the adoption of programming language innovation, and also argues that “the time is ripe for the principled examination of the sociology of programming languages”, Pinch and Bijker’s seminal paper on the Social Construction of Technological Artefacts [(Pinch and Bijker 1984\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?20rrTZ) finds no mention in this work.  Instead, much of the research relies on the work on innovation by economists.  In addition, the same authors also carried out empirical analysis of programming language adoption, leveraging a variety of data including polls, surveys and data from code hosting sites [(Meyerovich and Rabkin 2013\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?aUnJGI).  
Another related paper by Nofre examined in great detail the politics surrounding early programming languages.

# **Case Studies**

In this section, we will consider the variation and stabilisation of languages, by means of case studies of some still popular languages, and their associated variations and predecessors over time.

## **Java**

Java was created by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems, prior to its acquisition by Oracle.  As per Gosling, it was created out of a perceived lack of concern for security in C++ programs.  In his own words [(Anon n.d.-b)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?7cO26c), he was inspired by the culture in consumer electronics companies, who “viewed their relationship with the customer as sacred. They were never ever willing to make trade-offs for safety. One of the things that always made me nervous in the computer industry was that people were willing to make trade-offs in reliability to get performance.”  
This problem in C++ was resolved by taking away the work of managing memory from the programmer, and delegating it to the “Garbage Collector”.  Such garbage collectors are used in many successors of Java, like Go.  However, they can impact performance negatively, thus creating another problem for people who need high real-time performance like game developers.  Many developers resort to C++ for such needs.  However, a new language called Rust tries to avoid both the performance problem of Java as well as the safety problem of C++, by implementing techniques like the borrow checker.  
  	Another problem solved by Java was the ability to work across many different types of computers, as long as a “Virtual Machine” was installed on that system.  Gosling described in a recent interview [(Anon 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?d5T3rx) how Electrical Engineers at one of his employers, Three Rivers Computer Company, “wanted to do as little software as possible”.  The conception of the Virtual Machine came with the idea of having software written once and run on multiple machines, reducing the need to write software for each target machine.  
Seen retrospectively, we might be tempted to conceive of the evolution of Java as a linear process.  However, as Pinch and Bijker [(Pinch and Bijker 1984\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?QAluss) point out, this can hide the real dynamism and unpredictability of progress.  Instead, one would be served better by a framework that takes into account the problems faced by various stakeholders and the variations developed to serve their needs. ## **Javascript**

In the modern era of the world wide web, Javascript is a ubiquitous presence, having become theS most widely used programming language.  This success was by no means inevitable, given that it was a “sidekick scripting language”, created in 10 days by Brendan Eich at the young startup Netscape, and was even called “the worst invention ever”[(Wirfs-Brock and Eich 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5bcrh1)\!  
JavaScript’s influences were as chaotic as this environment.  Eich was instructed to create an “easy to use” language that would “look like Java”, which was the exciting new language at that time.  In addition, he also took ideas from C, Python, Self and Lisp.  This idiosyncratic lineage is a great argument against any Linear model of innovation.  
JavaScript has had many critics, but it has been able to become inescapable on the modern Web.  Many languages and other technologies attempt to improve upon JavaScript, trying to overcome various problems that it is felt to pose:

1. CoffeeScript: It tried to introduce “syntactic sugar” to javascript, by borrowing programmer-friendly syntax features from other languages, especially Ruby and Python.  Many of its ideas were appropriated by Javascript itself, leading to its obsolescence by 2015\.  
2. TypeScript: It brings in strong type safety to javascript, by borrowing strong type features from C\#, Java and similar languages.  It continues to be a popular language for web development, and might prove to be a strong contender to javascript in the years to come.

Most of these variations are obsolete at the moment, with the exception of Javascript.  
Some variations do not pose an alternative to JavaScript, but have become a part of javascript and its ecosystem itself:

1. V8: A high performance Javascript engine developed by Google in 2006 for the Chrome browser.  This led to huge performance gains for javascript, making javascript a serious high-performance language.  
2. Node.js: a framework for building server-side applications using javascript as a general purpose language.  This has the advantage of letting a programmer use the same language for both front end (on the client’s browser) and back end (on the server) development, reducing costs.

![][image2]  
This phenomenon of Javascript appropriating its variations into the language or the ecosystem is not accommodated by Pinch and Bijker’s framework at all. ## **Early Programming Languages**

	As pointed out in *The Evolution of Programming Languages* [(Horowitz 1983\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?zdKBHe), there was a boom in the development of programming languages in the 1950s and especially the 1960s, with some describing the field as a “Tower of Babel”.  Around this time, programming came to be seen as a legitimate field of science.  This transition both led to and was accelerated by the development of ALGOL [(Nofre 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LpRbFL).    
ALGOL60, in particular, had a substantial influence on programming language designers, and many languages came to be described as being “ALGOL-like”.  One major ALGOL-like language was SIMULA, developed by Dahl and Nygaard in Norway in the late 60s.  SIMULA, in turn went on to influence Bjarne Stroustrup in the development of C++, along with BCPL, another ALGOL descendent.    
Despite its pervasiveness in modern languages, ALGOL itself was not a success.  It has been suggested [(Nofre 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?9QitwB) that its strong research-oriented character might have been partly responsible for its downfall, and its inability to develop as reliable technology.  This idea brings to mind the suggestion [(Godin 2006\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?7JACr2) by the US DoD that research leads to only a minority of innovation.  Perhaps the instinct for Basic Research overtook many practical considerations.  Certainly, the descendents of ALGOL like C++ were designed to serve very practical needs.  
One language that broke the mould of ALGOL-like languages was LISP, which was developed in the late 1950s by John McCarthy at MIT.  This was despite the fact that McCarthy was himself part of the ALGOL design committee.   Similar to ALGOL, LISP has also remained a mainly academic language [(Gabriel 2000\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gVgtEK), in comparison to the more practical languages that have come to dominate programming.

# **Politics of Programming Languages**

As has been pointed out by Winner [(Winner 1980\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?CpThpV), technological artefacts can and do embody politics. ## **Java**

The Java Programming Language, then owned by Sun Microsystems, was released under the GNU Public License in 2007 [(LaMonica n.d.)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LOPXY0).  The GNU Public licence is an explicitly political one, motivated by reasons of transparency of knowledge.  Version 1 of the GPL was written by Richard Stallman in 1989, a pioneer of the Free Software Movement, who considered making software proprietary (i.e., not allowing the software to be modified and hiding its source code) to be an ‘injustice’.  According to Stallman, software should be free and anyone owning a copy of software should have the freedom to run, copy, distribute, study, change and improve it [(Anon n.d.-d)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6WXjvZ).  
The decision to release Java as open source probably allowed Sun to have more control over the distribution of the language.  In addition, a non-free version of Java had been distributed by Microsoft in the 1990s [(Anon 2015\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?vhcR4n), thereby fragmenting the Java platform and disadvantaged Sun.  Possibly as a pushback, it was released under the GPL.  This open-source nature of Java would make it inherently political, in that it supports decentralisation and prevents power from collecting at a single point.

## **Javascript**

In the 1990s, Javascript was a major component of the (first) Browser Wars, a series of struggles between Microsoft, which was then dominant in the Personal Computer market, and Netscape, a rising new company that had come to dominate the market for browsers for the then new world wide web.    
Microsoft was wary of the emergence of the Web, which would have been a cross-OS platform, which would potentially threaten the irreplaceability of their own Windows OS.  Given this scenario, Microsoft’s CEO reoriented the firm and established the creation of their own browser called Internet Explorer to compete with Netscape’s Navigator browser.  This set the stage for the Browser Wars, where Netscape and Microsoft tried to out-innovate each other [(Wirfs-Brock and Eich 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gco2dw).    
To start with, Microsoft asked Netscape to not allow its browser to work on their new Windows 95 OS.  In return, Microsoft would offer not to compete with Netscape on other (less popular) OSes.  This plan was rejected by Netscape.  In response, Microsoft started a campaign of anti-competitive behaviour (as claimed by the US Department of Justice), that included:

1. Forcing PC manufacturers and users to use their Internet Explorer browser in order to use the Windows Operating System  
2. “Welding” the Internet Explorer browser to the Windows 98 OS, making the use of another browser like Navigator a “jarring experience”.

In this way, both the decision by Netscape to bundle javascript in a platform-independent way in its browser and Microsoft’s counteroffensive to tightly-couple Internet Explorer and Windows 98 are an example of what Winner meant by “Technical Arrangements as Forms of Order”  [(Winner 1980\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?EU6xY3).  Netscape’s decision to bundle a platform-independent programmable language in its browser would have advanced its interests in the personal computing market, and helped it challenge the dominance of Microsoft.  On the other hand, Microsoft’s coupling of Windows 98 and Internet Explorer helped it maintain its own dominant position.  
Ultimately, Microsoft won out in the marketplace, and Netscape ended up being sold to AOL.  However, Microsoft’s tactics attracted the attention of Federal Regulatory authorities in the USA, which slapped them with an antitrust lawsuit [(Anon n.d.-a)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?SQa7Ce).

## **Algol**

	A paper by Nofre [(Nofre 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LcbUDX) has examined in great detail the politics surrounding the creation of the ALGOL language, and how it was influenced by tensions between political forces situated in the USA and Europe.  Apart from the shortcomings in ALGOL itself (being a research language as opposed to a practical one), another major aspect would be the political implications of the project.  
	ALGOL was conceived to allow greater interoperability between machines in various European universities and institutions.  In this era, IBM was the market leader in the computer industry in the USA, but code written for one of its machines couldn’t be used on other machines.  In contrast, the European market was relatively fragmented, and the goal of the European programming community was to reduce expenses by unifying the programmability of various machines.  This was a threat to IBM, as it earned great revenue from consultancy on its machines.  Because of this reason, IBM reduced its involvement in the development of ALGOL, and some contend that this was a factor in the failure of ALGOL.  In addition, IBM created other languages to allow interoperability of code written for its own machines, like PL/I.    
	Thus, ALGOL’s development was negatively influenced by the power dynamics of an international organisation, which didn’t want to allow its market dominance to be challenged [(Nofre 2021\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8aw6Ir).

# **Collectives of Humans and Programming Languages**

	In this essay, we have seen a rough history of computing in the period after the second world war, via the lens of programming languages.  As is clear, many of these languages emerged out of pressing needs of a specific era, in order to solve problems faced by various stakeholders.  The recency of this field lets us examine it via the lens of Bruno Latour’s framework of human and non-human collectives [(Latour and Latour 1999\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?WBVTRg).  We can confirm that nonhuman programming languages have influenced human actors over the course of programming language history:

1. Programming languages can and do influence the behaviour of the programmer [(Weinberg 1998\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jH1ruK). For example, programming as an activity might induce programmers to be more humble and assertive.  Also, different languages might “allow” the programmer to express ideas more or less freely [(Meyerovich and Rabkin 2013\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?TfLD3B).  
2. As we can see in the case of Javascript, activity on the Web entails a coordinated effort by human programmers, language designers and users in concert with nonhuman artefacts like computers, software and languages.  
3. As programming languages evolved from simple machine instructions to higher level languages, much of the work that is performed by the program appears to be a simple act performed by a user.  However, if we look closely in this black box of a program, we can see that it involves a network of the programmer, the user and various stakeholders that led to the design decisions that comprise the language, the underlying operating system and the program.  Indeed, this idea is somewhat acknowledged in the industry, which adopts “black box testing” to refer to testing a program without being concerned with its inner details.  
4. A number of engineers and language designers developed languages (like Java) to perform various acts like memory management automatically.  This way, the garbage collector artefact stands in for the work done by these language designers.

Overall, Latour’s framework is well-suited for examining programming languages.  Also, the Department of Justice case was brought against Microsoft not on behalf of any person or even a company, but in order to preserve competition in the Web economy.  One could argue that the Web economy thus became a political ecology requiring its own representation.  
	Thus, we can see that non-human programming languages act along with a human programmer, as “actants”.  The manner in which they do so is by means of affordances, in the sense of Jenny Davis [(Davis and Chouinard 2016\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?v3htyo).  For example,

1. As mentioned by Meyerovich and Rabkin, higher level functional languages *allow* ideas to be expressed freely by the programmer.  
2. Garbage Collected languages like Java *refuse* arbitrary pointer arithmetic by the programmer.  
3. Languages like Rust, with its borrow checker, *discourage* unsafe programming practices by making constructs like mutable variables difficult to use.

	In this way, non-human programming languages employ their agency and act with the programmer to perform a programming practice.

# **Conclusion**

	In this text, we went over the history of development of programming languages, and approached the social construction of programming languages, using the SCOT framework developed by Pinch and Bijker.    
	In particular, we examined the development of three programming languages as case studies.  These three Case Studies indicate that the SCOT framework can be applied to the study of Programming Languages.  However, it falls short in some regards, especially when considering the appropriation of some variations by the dominant variation.  In all three cases, new languages developed as variations on previous languages, with the express purpose of addressing problems faced by some social groups.    
Additionally, it can also be seen that programming languages often embody politics, in ways that may be explicit or implicit.  For example, the Java Programming Language was released under the GPL, an explicitly political legal framework.    
It is useful to view programming languages as nonhuman actors in a network alongside human programmers, who act together to perform various practices.  This is compatible with the  Actor Network Theory of Bruno Latour.  
Overall, one can conclude that it is correct to see Programming Languages are socially constructed artefacts, with embodied politics.  However, it would be more complete to see them also as non-human actors within the Actor Network Theory framework.  Thus, although the Social Construction of Technology is a valid approach to seeing the development of programming languages, one can have a more robust picture by incorporating ideas from the Actor Network Theory.  
There is a surprising paucity of research on the sociology of Programming Languages, despite the maturity of the field and its relevance to the modern digital world.  Future studies might be well served with more empirical research.
